<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="440" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,865,1180]" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,865,891]" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ren et Pang" authorityName="Ren et Pang" box="[573,849,865,892]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Axinoscymnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glotticus">
<emphasis box="[573,701,865,892]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">A. glotticus</emphasis>
Ren et Pang
</taxonomicName>
in male genitalia but can be distinguished from the latter by the yellowish brown elytra with dark brown markings at humeral and apical parts, and the penis guide widest at base, then gradually converging to a pointed tip in lateral view. In 
<taxonomicName box="[961,1088,937,964]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Axinoscymnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glotticus">
<emphasis box="[961,1088,937,964]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">A. glotticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, elytra are brown without dark markings, and penis guide widest at base in lateral view, then sharply converging to a pointed tip (
<figureCitation box="[1250,1329,973,1000]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,996,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-282@8.[151,1436,987,1895]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Axinoscymnus glotticus Ren et Pang, 1992 (Holotype): a dorsal view b lateral view c frontal view d abdomen e penis f tegmen, lateral view g tegmen, inner view h labels of holotype. Scale bars: a–c: 0.5 mm, d: 0.1 mm, e–g: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6651171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6651171/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">Fig. 5f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
